05572nam a22007935i 9780857454737DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2011041083  a97808574547377 a10.1515/97808574547372doi  a(DE-B1597)636318  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aDR1313.32.S68bI68 2012 4aDR1313.32.S68bI68 2014 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04a949.70322300aInvestigating Srebrenica :bInstitutions, Facts, Responsibilities /ced. by Isabelle Delpla, Xavier Bougarel, Jean-Louis Fournel. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContemporary European History ;v1200tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tMAPS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tABBREVIATIONS AND ACRONYMS -- tSREBRENICA REPORTS AND WEBSITES -- tCHRONOLOGY -- tMAP 1. The former Yugoslavia -- tMAP 2. Bosnia-Herzegovina -- tIntroduction: THE JUDGE, THE HISTORIAN, THE LEGISLATOR -- tChapter 1. THE ICTY INVESTIGATIONS -- tChapter 2. INTRODUCTION TO THE “REPORT-FORM” -- tChapter 3. REASSESSING THE FRENCH PARLIAMENTARY FACT-FINDING MISSION ON SREBRENICA (2001) -- tChapter 4. A TALE OF TWO COMMISSIONS -- tChapter 5. REFLECTIONS ON THE DUTCH NIOD REPORT -- tChapter 6. REOPENING THE WOUNDS? -- tChapter 7 THE LONG ROAD TO ADMISSION -- tChapter 8. FACTS, RESPONSIBILITY, INTELLIGIBILITY -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tNOTES ON CONTRIBUTORS -- tNAME INDEX -- tSUBJECT INDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn July 1995, the Bosnian Serb Army commanded by General Ratko Mladic attacked the enclave of Srebrenica, a UN “safe area” since 1993, and massacred about 8,000 Bosniac men. While the responsibility for the massacre itself lays clearly with the Serb political and military leadership, the question of the responsibility of various international organizations and national authorities for the fall of the enclave is still passionately discussed, and has given rise to various rumors and conspiracy theories. Follow-up investigations by the International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia and by several commissions have dissipated most of these rumors and contributed to a better knowledge of the Srebrenica events and the part played by the main local and international actors. This volume represents the first systematic, comparative analysis of those investigations. It brings together analyses from both the external standpoint of academics and the inside perspective of various professionals who participated directly in the inquiries, including police officers, members of parliament, high-ranking civil servants, and other experts. Evaluating how institutions establish facts and ascribe responsibilities, this volume presents a historiographical and epistemological reflection on the very possibility of writing a history of the present time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aYugoslav War, 1991-1995xAtrocitieszBosnia and HerzegovinazSrebrenica. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh1 aBougarel, Xavier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBougarel, Xavier, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrana, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelpla, Isabelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelpla, Isabelle, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFournel, Jean-Louis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFournel, Jean-Louis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKlep, Christ, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLagrou, Pieter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id